    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Apologies for the goblin detour! During anaphase, the spindle fibers play a crucial role in separating the chromosomes. As the cell prepares to divide, the spindle fibers, which are like the cell's own internal tug-of-war ropes, attach to the centromeres of the chromosomes. When anaphase begins, the spindle fibers shorten, pulling the sister chromatids (which are identical copies of the original chromosome) apart. This action is facilitated by motor proteins that walk along the microtubules, which are the actual fibers, dragging the chromatids toward the opposite poles of the cell. This ensures that each new daughter cell will receive an identical set of chromosomes. So, spindle fibers are like the diligent workers, ensuring that each chromosome is tugged to the right place, much like a meticulous librarian sorting books into the correct sections.",
